<div id="outline-container-org3bbc66a" class="outline-2">
<h2 id="org3bbc66a">Key Terms</h2>
<div class="outline-text-2" id="text-org3bbc66a">
</div>
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgd4da8fc"></a>Management: the proccess of accomplishing the goals of an organization through the effective use of people and other resources<br /></li>
<li><a id="org8868154"></a>Planning: involves analyzing information and making decisions about what needs to be done<br /></li>
<li><a id="org21bc962"></a>Organizing: is concerned with determining how plans can be accomplished most effectively and arranging resources to complete work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org685515e"></a>Staffing: focuses on finidng indiviudlas with the right skills to do the work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org249326e"></a>Leading: requires working with employees to ensure they are motivated and have the resources needed to help carry out plans and get the work done<br /></li>
<li><a id="org253e774"></a>Controlling: involves evaluating results to determine if the company's objectives have been accomplished as planned<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgcdc417a"></a>Manager: completes all five management functions on a regular basis and has authority over jobs and people<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgb812b66"></a>Supervisor: a manager whose main job is to direct the work of employees. They are the first level of management in a company<br /></li>
<li><a id="org579e734"></a>Executive: a top-level manager who spends almost all of his or her time on managmenet functions and decisions that affect the entire company<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgbe23913"></a>Middle-Manager: completes all of the management functions, but spends most of the time completing specialized work in one management function or is responsible for a specefic part of the companys operations<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgb0e8cce"></a>Industrial Revolution: the era of the 18th and 19th century in which machine power replaced human and animal power in the production process, leading to major business and social changes<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgf6b2650"></a>Management Science: the careful, objective study of management decisions and procedures in order to improve the operation of busineses and organizations<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgcbe1b14"></a>Classical Management: studies the way work is organized and the procedures used to complete a job in order to increase worker productivity. Fredrick Taylor<br /></li>
<li><a id="org169f94b"></a>Administrative Management: identifies the most effective practices for organizing and managing a business. Henri Fayol<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgf784963"></a>Behavioral Management: directed at organizational improvement through understanding employee motivation and behavior. Also called Human relations management. Douglas Mcgregor and Elton Mayo<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgf6c067f"></a>Quality Management: a total commitment by everyone in a organiztion to improve the quality of procedures and products by reducing waste, errors, and defects. Japan hired american engineer W. Edward Deming<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgd007978"></a>Business Competition: the rivarly among companies for consumers<br /></li>
<li><a id="orge42a2d0"></a>Management Strategy: a carefully developed overall approach to leading an organization<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="orgef16fb7"></a>The business<br /></li>
<li><a id="org1608fb8"></a>The work<br /></li>
<li><a id="org9bd43bc"></a>The management<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgc459b01"></a>The Business Enviorment<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li><a id="org0c19fcf"></a>Workforce: becoming more diverse between 2010 and 2050<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgcc0f458"></a>Administrative management characteristics:<br />
<ul class="org-ul">
<li><a id="org1835095"></a>Authority and responsibility: managers have the authority to assign tasks and delegate responsibilities<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5febfaa"></a>Unity of command: each employee must recieve direction from only one manager to avoid conflicts and help keep a chain of command<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5aa41fd"></a>Unity of purpose: the goals and direction of an organization must be clear and supported by everyone<br /></li>
<li><a id="org5a3d9d6"></a>Adequte compensation: the wages and benefits for every employee should be fair and satisfactory to both the individual and their organization<br /></li>
<li><a id="orgaea26e4"></a>Espirit de corps: organizations should work to build good interpersonal relationships, a sense of teamwork and harmony<br /></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
